/***
  
  JelGamal 
  A conceptual ElGamal implementation, not intended for real world application.
  J Gericke
  (julian@jbg.za.org)

  --------------------
  El Gamal Encryption:
  Let p be a prime, and g be a generator of Zp. The private key x is an integer between 1 and p − 2. Let y = g x mod p. The public key for El Gamal 
  encryption is the triplet (p, g, y). If taking discrete logarithms is as difficult as it is widely believed, releasing y = g x mod p does not reveal x.
  To encrypt a plaintext M, a random integer k relatively prime to p − 1 is selected, and the following pair of values is computed: a = g&k mod p and 
  b = M(y^k mod p). The ciphertext C consists of the pair (a, b) computed above. 

  El Gamal Decryption
  The decryption of the ciphertext C = (a, b) in the El Gamal scheme, to retrieve the plaintext M, is simple: M = b/ax mod p (El Gamal decryption).
  In the above expression, the “division” by ax should be interpreted in the context of modular arithmetic, that is, M is multiplied by the inverse of 
  ax in Zp . The correctness of the El Gamal encryption scheme is easy to verify. Indeed, we have b/ax mod p = My k (ax )−1 mod p = Mg xk (g kx )−1 mod p
  = M.

***/

